Day - 1
Introduction about jira
Jira terminologies

Jira by Atlassian
  •	Jira is a powerful project management and issue-tracking tool used by teams (software, IT, marketing and business) to plan, track and release work,
  supporting agile methodologies like Scrum and Kanban with features for bug tracking, task management, custom workflows, and reporting, serving as a 
  central hub to organize projects and improve collaboration. 

Jira Terminologies
  Core Concepts
    •	Issue: A fundamental unit of work (work item)
    •	Project: A collection/container of related issues
    •	Issue Type: Classification of issues (epic, bug, task, story etc)
    •	Boards: Visualizing issues (kanban/scrum)
    •	Workflow: The defined path an issue follows
  Agile & Scrum Terms
    •	Epic: A large body of work, broken down into smaller stories
    •	Story: A user-centric requirement
    •	Task: A generic piece of work
    •	Bug: A defect or error
    •	Sprint: A fixed time period to complete work
    •	Backlog: The prioritized list of all pending work
    •	Burndown Chart: Visualizes work remaining vs time in a sprint
  Views & Tools
    •	Dashboards: Customizable overview with gadgets (charts, stats)
    •	JQL: Jira Query Language a powerful search syntax for issues
    •	Custom field: A user defined field to capture extra data
    •	Component: A sub-section or feature within a project
  Statuses & States
    •	To Do/Open: Ready to start
    •	In Progress/Work in Progress: Actively being worked on
    •	In Review/Under Review: Awaiting peer check
    •	Done/Closed/Resolved: Work completed
    •	Cancelled/Won’t Do: Work stopped
  Jira Products
    •	Jira Software (JSW): For Development Teams (Scrum/Kanban)
    •	Jira Service Management (JSM): For IT/Customer support
    •	Jira Work Management (JWM): For Business Teams
